+## TIER 1 — Production Blockers (Ship-stopping for target users)
+
+### 1.1 Mobile Reading System for Long Documents
+- **Category:** MISSING
+- **Severity:** CRITICAL
+- **Location:** `src/frontend/web/src/app/document/page.tsx`, new `ReadingContext` provider
+- **Current state:** Static safe-HTML renderer with metadata masthead and bottom-sheet actions. No affordances for 10,000+ word DOU documents on mobile. Users must manually scroll with no orientation, no resume, no way to share a specific position.
+- **What is needed:**
+  1. **Floating TOC access (FAB):** Slide-out sheet on mobile triggered by a persistent button. Uses IntersectionObserver on heading elements to highlight the active section.
+  2. **Reading progress indicator:** Thin bar at top of viewport or section-based fraction (e.g., "Seção 3 de 7"). Scroll-percentage alone is insufficient for legal docs — section-based is more meaningful.
+  3. **Resume reading position:** Persist `{ documentId, scrollY, sectionId, timestamp }` to localStorage. On return visit, prompt "Continuar de onde parou?" with one-tap restore.
+  4. **Share-at-position deep linking:** URL param `?section=<id>` that scrolls-to and highlights the target section on load. Enables citation sharing between researchers.
+- **Why it matters:** DOU documents are routinely 5,000–30,000 words. Without navigation affordances, mobile reading is physically unusable. This is the single highest-impact gap for the stated "mobile reading" product goal.
+- **Implementation order:** FIRST. Unblocks the core use case.
+- **Estimated scope:** ~3–4 days. ReadingContext provider + IntersectionObserver hook + TOC sheet component + localStorage persistence + URL param handling.
+
+### 1.2 Semantic Tabular Detector for Structured Content
+- **Category:** MISSING
+- **Severity:** CRITICAL
+- **Location:** New module `src/frontend/web/src/lib/content-renderers/tabular-detector.ts`, consumed by document renderer
+- **Current state:** All document content passes through a generic safe-HTML renderer. Documents containing tabular data (concurso editais, procurement tables, salary grids) render as undifferentiated paragraph walls. Critical structured information is visually destroyed.
+- **What is needed:**
+  1. **DOM analysis pass** before render: detect sequences of `<p>` tags containing delimiters (`|`, `R$`, sequential numbering, repeated structural patterns like "Cargo: ... Vagas: ... Remuneração: ...").
+  2. **Heuristic classifier** for known DOU document types: `EDITAL`, `EXTRATO DE CONTRATO`, `RESULTADO DE JULGAMENTO`. These have predictable internal structure.
+  3. **Transform detected structures** into responsive `<table>` elements with sticky headers on mobile, horizontal scroll on narrow viewports.
+  4. **Fallback:** If heuristic confidence is below threshold, render original HTML unchanged. Never corrupt content by misdetecting structure.
+- **Why it matters:** Concurso/procurement research is one of the highest-traffic DOU use cases. Rendering tables as text walls makes the tool unreliable for its primary audience. Legal professionals will use the official gazette PDF instead — which defeats the product's purpose.
+- **Implementation order:** SECOND. Directly after mobile reading, because it affects document rendering quality at the same layer.
+- **Estimated scope:** ~3 days. Heuristic engine + responsive table component + test suite against sample DOU documents.
