+## TIER 3 — Quality-of-Life Improvements (Enhances but doesn't block)
+
+### 3.1 Home Information Density
+- **Category:** PARTIAL (layout exists but density is too low for the data-heavy use case)
+- **Severity:** MEDIUM
+- **Location:** `src/frontend/web/src/app/page.tsx`, metric cards, featured document card, search chips
+- **Current state:** Excessive padding on metric cards, featured document card consumes ~40%+ viewport height, search chips lack secondary metadata.
+- **What is needed:**
+  1. Reduce card padding (`p-6` → `p-3` on desktop, keep `p-4` on mobile for touch targets).
+  2. Convert featured document to horizontal compact layout on desktop (thumbnail left, metadata right). Keep stacked on mobile.
+  3. Add micro-metadata to search chips: trend indicator ("+12% hoje") or last-updated timestamp.
+  4. Consider bento-grid layout for dashboard section instead of single-column stack on desktop.
+- **Why it matters:** Information density is a competitive differentiator against the official gazette. If researchers see the same amount of information per screen, they have no reason to switch. Higher density = faster scanning = more value per session.
+- **Implementation order:** SIXTH. Can be done incrementally alongside other work.
+- **Estimated scope:** ~1–2 days. CSS/layout changes + chip metadata enrichment.
+
+### 3.2 Recent History Wiring
+- **Category:** PARTIAL (empty state UI exists, persistence and click handlers do not)
+- **Severity:** MEDIUM
+- **Location:** `src/frontend/web/src/app/page.tsx`, new `useReadingHistory` hook
+- **Current state:** Home shows a recent-history section with an empty state message. No localStorage persistence of viewed documents. No click handlers to navigate back to a document at the last-read position.
+- **What is needed:**
+  1. `useReadingHistory` hook that writes `{ documentId, title, organ, lastReadAt, scrollPosition, sectionId }` to localStorage on document view.
+  2. Home page reads from this hook and renders history cards with document title, organ, time-ago, and a "Continuar lendo" action.
+  3. Click handler navigates to document page with scroll position restore (ties into §1.1 resume reading).
+  4. Swipe-to-dismiss on mobile for history items. Clear-all action.
+- **Why it matters:** Without history, returning users start from zero every session. This is the simplest retention mechanism.
+- **Implementation order:** SEVENTH. Partially blocked by §1.1 (resume reading position), since the history click should restore position.
+- **Estimated scope:** ~1 day (assumes §1.1 ReadingContext already exists).
